Pºt RAL *ſūx ICIPALITIES. i On the question of rural organisation the Premier said there was no ques­tion that there was a necessity for snine organisation in this country. A TERRITORIAL UNIVE::siTY.

With reference to the creatinn of a Territorial University, Premier Haul­tain º with the previous speakers that the Territories were not prepared tº establish a University at Önce, but Mr. Lambert had struck the right note when he said that the time to prepare the frame work for some such univer. sity had arrived. H. had assurance from the Federal Gov ernment that they were prepared to set aside a liberal land grant for uni­versity purposes in the West. (Cheers.) Our own lands in the West, I should say, corrected the Premier. The ob­ject in bringing in legislation at this tline was, to use a common expression. to make a peg on which to hang a land grant. The Prentier then referred to the kind of a university required in the West, James Russell Lowell had once said that a university was a place where a great many things of no use were taught. This was not the kind of a university required and proposed in the West. It would he for the ad­vancerrient and diffusion of useful knowledge, where scientific research could he followed out in close connec­tion with every business in the Terri­tories, every commercial enterprise, our mines, our agriculture, everything that, is gºing to make this cºuntry great. The connection of scientific research with these subjects was too well known to need taking np the time of the House to show the importance of providing the same. They should establish one institution for the whole Territories, an institution open to all, where all would have equal : privileges, both rich and poor alike., { where the young men of the coun whether rich or poor, no matter what their beginnings, may have the privi­lege of developing their talente in this country. It must he free cf all sec­tarian control and all political control and have no connection whatever with any denomination or pºlitical party. It imust be an institution “for the peo­ple and of the people” in the best accep­tation of that phrase. (Cheers).
